# UI System Reference

The UI system provides immediate-mode rendering for both screen-space and world-space interfaces.

## Core Principles

1. **Y grows upward** - (0, 0) is the bottom-left of the screen
2. **Start from screen rects** - Derive all UI from `UI.ScreenRect` (centered/fullscreen) or `UI.SafeRect` (edges/corners respecting notches)
3. **Push/pop pattern** - Use `using var _ =` for automatic cleanup
4. **Mobile-first** - Avoid hover effects; design for touch interaction
5. **Only ASCII** - No emoji support; use text and icons only
6. **UI functions should be static** - Take inputs as parameters
7. **NEVER call new Rect()** - Always derive from screen rects

## Where to Draw Interactive UI

Player-interactable UI (buttons, scroll views, etc.) **must** be drawn inside `Update()` or `LateUpdate()`. 

Always check `Network.IsServer` or use `IsLocal` for the player:

```csharp
public override void Update()
{
    if (Network.IsServer) return;
    
    var local = Network.LocalPlayer as MyPlayer;
    if (local == null || !local.Alive()) return;
    
    DrawMyHUD(local);
}

static void DrawMyHUD(MyPlayer player)
{
    var rect = UI.SafeRect.BottomRightRect().Grow(40, 100, 40, 100).Offset(-50, 50);
    var bs = new UI.ButtonSettings();
    var ts = GetTextSettings(24);

    if (UI.Button(rect, "Action", bs, ts).Clicked)
    {
        player.CallServer_DoAction();
    }
}
```

## Basic Drawing

### Images and Quads

```csharp
// Draw a textured quad
var rect = UI.ScreenRect.CenterRect().Grow(100); // 200x200 at center
var texture = Assets.GetAsset<Texture>("ui/my_icon.png");
UI.Image(rect, texture);

// With color tint (RGBA Vector4, values 0-1)
UI.Image(rect, texture, new Vector4(1, 0, 0, 0.5f)); // Red, 50% transparent

// Solid color using white sprite
UI.Image(rect, UI.WhiteSprite, new Vector4(0, 0, 0, 0.75f));
```

### Text

```csharp
var rect = UI.ScreenRect.CenterRect().Grow(200, 300, 50, 300);
var ts = GetTextSettings(48);

// Async text (most common - does not block)
UI.TextAsync(rect, "Hello, World!", ts);

// Sync text returns actual rendered rect (useful for dynamic layouts)
var actualRect = UI.TextSync(rect, "Dynamic text", ts);
```

### Text Settings

```csharp
var ts = new UI.TextSettings()
{
    Font = UI.Fonts.BarlowBold,
    Size = 32,
    Color = Vector4.White,
    HorizontalAlignment = UI.HorizontalAlignment.Center, // Left, Center, Right
    VerticalAlignment = UI.VerticalAlignment.Center,     // Top, Center, Bottom
    Offset = new Vector2(0, 0),
    Outline = true,
    OutlineThickness = 3,
    OutlineColor = new Vector4(0, 0, 0, 1),
    DropShadowColor = new Vector4(0, 0, 0.02f, 0.5f),
    DropShadowOffset = new Vector2(0, -3),
    WordWrap = false,
};
```

## Rect Functions Reference

```csharp
// Position rects (0x0 point rects)
rect.CenterRect()
rect.TopLeftRect(), rect.TopRightRect()
rect.BottomLeftRect(), rect.BottomRightRect()
rect.LeftCenterRect(), rect.RightCenterRect()
rect.TopCenterRect(), rect.BottomCenterRect()

// Edge rects (line-shaped: one dimension is full, one is zero)
rect.LeftRect()    // 0 x height
rect.RightRect()   // 0 x height  
rect.TopRect()     // width x 0
rect.BottomRect()  // width x 0

// Manipulation (values scaled by UI scale factor)
rect.Inset(top, right, bottom, left)
rect.Inset(all)
rect.InsetTop(pixels), InsetRight, InsetBottom, InsetLeft

rect.Grow(top, right, bottom, left)
rect.Grow(all)
rect.GrowTop(pixels), GrowRight, GrowBottom, GrowLeft

rect.CutTop(pixels)    // Returns cut portion, modifies rect
rect.CutRight(pixels)
rect.CutBottom(pixels)
rect.CutLeft(pixels)

rect.Offset(x, y)      // Move without changing size
rect.Scale(all)        // Multiply dimensions
rect.Scale(x, y)
rect.Slide(x, y)       // Move by percentage of own size

rect.FitAspect(aspect) // For icons/images
rect.FitAspect(aspect, FitAspectKind.KeepWidth)
rect.FitAspect(aspect, FitAspectKind.KeepHeight)

rect.SubRect(x1, y1, x2, y2) // Percentage-based (for health bars)

// Properties
rect.Width, rect.Height
rect.Center, rect.TopLeft, rect.BottomRight
```

### Edge Rects vs Point Rects - IMPORTANT

`LeftRect()`, `RightRect()`, `TopRect()`, `BottomRect()` return **line-shaped rects**. If you `Grow()` from these, the result is rectangular, not square.

```csharp
// WRONG: Creates tall rectangle because LeftRect() has full height
var button = slider.LeftRect().Grow(20).Offset(20, 0);

// CORRECT: Use a point rect like LeftCenterRect() to grow into a square
var button = slider.LeftCenterRect().Grow(20).Offset(20, 0);
```

### Auto-scaling and Unscaled Functions

All rect functions automatically multiply by UI scale factor (screen height / 1080). Values are "pixels if 1080p".

When using **computed pixel values** (like a rect's width), use `_Unscaled` variants:

```csharp
// WRONG: Double-scaling if scale factor != 1
listBase = listBase.Offset(0, -listBase.Height);

// CORRECT: Use unscaled with exact pixel values
listBase = listBase.OffsetUnscaled(0, -listBase.Height);
```

Available unscaled functions:
- `OffsetUnscaled`, `InsetUnscaled`, `GrowUnscaled`
- `CutTopUnscaled`, `CutRightUnscaled`, `CutBottomUnscaled`, `CutLeftUnscaled`
- `InsetTopUnscaled`, `GrowTopUnscaled`, etc.

### Cutting Pattern (Most Important!)

`Cut` snips a portion off a rect and returns that portion. **Use for sequential layouts to avoid overlap:**

```csharp
var rect = UI.SafeRect;
var header = rect.CutTop(60);    // Returns 60px from top, rect shrinks
var footer = rect.CutBottom(40); // Returns 40px from bottom
var sidebar = rect.CutLeft(200); // Returns 200px from left
var content = rect;              // Remaining space

// Space is removed as you allocate it - no overlap possible
```

### Grid Layout

For grids of equally-sized elements:

```csharp
var grid = UI.GridLayout.Make(rect, 4, 6, UI.GridLayout.SizeSource.ElementCount, padding: 8);

for (int i = 0; i < items.Count; i++)
{
    using var _ = UI.PUSH_ID(i);
    var slotRect = grid.Next();
    // Draw item...
}
```

Grids start at top-left and advance right, then down.

## Buttons

```csharp
var rect = UI.SafeRect.BottomCenterRect().Grow(40, 150, 40, 150).Offset(0, 100);

var bs = new UI.ButtonSettings()
{
    Sprite = Assets.GetAsset<Texture>("$AO/new/modal/buttons_2/button_2.png"),
    Slice = new UI.NineSlice() { slice = new Vector4(45, 45, 45, 45), sliceScale = 0.35f },
    PressScaling = 0.35f,
    ColorMultiplier = Vector4.White,
    BackgroundColorMultiplier = Vector4.White, // Just the sprite, not text
};

var ts = GetTextSettings(24);
var result = UI.Button(rect, "Click Me!", bs, ts);

if (result.Clicked)
{
    Log.Info("Button clicked!");
}
```

### Button Results

```csharp
result.Clicked;   // Was clicked (pressed and released)
result.Active;    // Being actively interacted with
result.Hovering;  // Mouse is over (PC only)
```

## UI State Management

### Push/Pop Pattern

Always use `using var _ =` for automatic cleanup:

```csharp
// Layers (higher = drawn on top)
using var _layer = UI.PUSH_LAYER(100);
using var _relLayer = UI.PUSH_LAYER_RELATIVE(10);

// Z depth (for 3D sorting in world space)
using var _z = IM.PUSH_Z(5.0f);

// Scale factor
using var _scale = UI.PUSH_SCALE_FACTOR(1.5f);

// Color multiplier
using var _color = UI.PUSH_COLOR_MULTIPLIER(new Vector4(1, 1, 1, 0.5f));

// World context
using var _world = UI.PUSH_CONTEXT(UI.Context.WORLD);
```

### UI IDs - REQUIRED for repeated elements

When drawing multiple similar elements, push unique IDs:

```csharp
for (int i = 0; i < items.Count; i++)
{
    using var _ = UI.PUSH_ID(i);  // Unique ID for each button
    
    var itemRect = rect.CutTop(60);
    if (UI.Button(itemRect, items[i].Name, bs, ts).Clicked)
    {
        SelectItem(i);
    }
}
```

## World Space UI

For UI in the game world (health bars, name tags). **Use meters - characters are ~1 meter tall.**

```csharp
using var _ctx = UI.PUSH_CONTEXT(UI.Context.WORLD);
using var _z = IM.PUSH_Z(entity.Y - 0.001f);

var pos = entity.Position;
var barPos = pos + new Vector2(0, 1.5f); // 1.5m above

// Health bar: 0.2m tall, 1m wide
var barRect = new Rect(
    barPos - new Vector2(0.5f, 0.1f),
    barPos + new Vector2(0.5f, 0.1f)
);

UI.Image(barRect, UI.WhiteSprite, new Vector4(0, 0, 0, 0.8f));

// Fill using SubRect for percentage
float healthPct = entity.Health / entity.MaxHealth;
var fillRect = barRect.Inset(0.02f).SubRect(0, 0, healthPct, 1);
UI.Image(fillRect, UI.WhiteSprite, new Vector4(0, 1, 0, 1));
```

## Scroll Views

```csharp
var sv = UI.PushScrollView("my_scroll", rect, new UI.ScrollViewSettings() { Vertical = true });
{
    var contentRect = sv.contentRect;
    
    for (int i = 0; i < items.Count; i++)
    {
        var itemRect = contentRect.CutTop(40);
        UI.TextAsync(itemRect, items[i], ts);
    }
}
UI.PopScrollView();
```

## Common Text Settings Helper

```csharp
static UI.TextSettings GetTextSettings(float size, Vector4? color = null)
{
    return new UI.TextSettings()
    {
        Font = UI.Fonts.BarlowBold,
        Size = size,
        Color = color ?? Vector4.White,
        DropShadowColor = new Vector4(0f, 0f, 0.02f, 0.5f),
        DropShadowOffset = new Vector2(0f, -3f),
        HorizontalAlignment = UI.HorizontalAlignment.Center,
        VerticalAlignment = UI.VerticalAlignment.Center,
        Outline = true,
        OutlineThickness = 3,
    };
}
```

## [UIPreview] Decorator

For testing UI in the editor without running the game:

```csharp
[UIPreview]
public static void PreviewMyUI()
{
    DrawMyUI("Example Title", 75, true);
}

public static void DrawMyUI(string title, int progress, bool showButton)
{
    var rect = UI.ScreenRect.CenterRect().Grow(200, 300, 200, 300);
    // ... draw UI
}
```

**Never call Entity.Create in UIPreview functions** - entities will pile up in the editor.

